chinese ink rubbings on display at the art & architecture library sulair sulair home searchworks e journals databases off campus access ask us sulair news logo sulair news home all articles submit article search sulair news library web sites searchworks databases az socrates google books google scholar search this site sulair news about sulair news back issues get email announcements submit article user login login with your sunet id home groups sulair news chinese ink rubbings on display at the art & architecture library the art & architecture library is currently displaying six sets of hanging scrolls in the exhibition carved in stone a selection of chinese ink rubbings from the art locked stacks collection in chinese culture rubbings are seen as more than mere copies since each one is unique they are seen as works of art in their own right there are several names for rubbings in chinese but they are commonly referred to as black tigers hei laohu   by collectors and connoisseurs because of their color and because of the number of fraudulent rubbings on the market that can bite an unsuspecting buyer the technique of making ink rubbings of stone and metal inscriptions is believed to have originated in china by the liang dynasty 502 556 ce but perhaps as early as the han dynasty 206 bce 220 ce the works shown in this exhibition are all rubbings taken from stelae vertical stone monuments usually engraved with writings of widely varying dates additionally the exhibition wear when historical and contemporary representations of costume and fashion continues through the winter quarter come visit us in the art & architecture library reading room to view these two demonstrations of the library's exceptional holdings anna fishaut art & architecture library submitted by afishaut stanfo on sat 01 16 2010 11 23 back stanford university stanford california 94305 650 725 1064 terms of use copyright complaints
